04345nam a22005895i 9780226522890DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265228907 a10.7208/97802265228902doi  a(DE-B1597)521378  a(OCoLC)1028211122  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aML1727.3b.B56 2019 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a782.109442231 aBloechl, Olivia, eauthor.10aOpera and the Political Imaginary in Old Regime France /cOlivia Bloechl. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b9 halftones, 31 line drawings, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tEditorial Principles -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Sovereignty and Government in the Tragédie en musique -- tChapter One. The Politics of Glory: Angelic Citizenship and the Contemplative Chorus -- tChapter Two. Choral Lament and the Mourning Public -- tChapter Three. True Confessions: Opera's Theater of Guilt and Remorse -- tChapter Four. The Tormenting Orchestra -- tChapter Five. Spectral Kingdoms: Poetics and Politics of Les Enfers -- tChapter Six. Pluto, the Underworld King -- tConclusion: A Theater of Precarity -- tAppendix. Operas and Ballets Cited -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its origins in the 1670s through the French Revolution, serious opera in France was associated with the power of the absolute monarchy, and its ties to the crown remain at the heart of our understanding of this opera tradition (especially its foremost genre, the tragédie en musique).   In Opera and the Political Imaginary in Old Regime France, however, Olivia Bloechl reveals another layer of French opera's political theater. The make-believe worlds on stage, she shows, involved not just fantasies of sovereign rule but also aspects of government. Plot conflicts over public conduct, morality, security, and law thus appear side-by-side with tableaus hailing glorious majesty. What's more, opera's creators dispersed sovereign-like dignity and powers well beyond the genre's larger-than-life rulers and gods, to its lovers, magicians, and artists. This speaks to the genre's distinctive combination of a theological political vocabulary with a concern for mundane human capacities, which is explored here for the first time.   By looking at the political relations among opera characters and choruses in recurring scenes of mourning, confession, punishment, and pardoning, we can glimpse a collective political experience underlying, and sometimes working against, ancienrégime absolutism. Through this lens, French opera of the period emerges as a deeply conservative, yet also more politically nuanced, genre than previously thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aOperaxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy17th century. 0aOperaxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aOperazFrancey17th century. 0aOperazFrancey18th century. 4aAncien Regime. 4aFoucault. 4aFrance. 4aearly modern. 4aopera. 4apolitics. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226522890423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226522890.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles